NAME
    sort - sort lines of text

SYNOPSIS
    sort [options] [file...]
    <input> | sort [options]

DESCRIPTION
    Sorts lines of text. Reads from files or stdin if no files specified.
    By default, sorts alphabetically by entire line.

OPTIONS
    -r              Reverse the sort order
    -n              Sort numerically
    -u              Output only unique lines (remove duplicates)
    -f              Fold case (case-insensitive sort)
    -b              Ignore leading blanks
    -d              Dictionary order (only alphanumeric and space)
    -h              Human numeric sort (2K, 1M, 3G)
    -k <key>        Sort by field (e.g., -k2 or -k2,3)
    -t <sep>        Field separator (default: whitespace)
    -o <file>       Write output to file instead of stdout
    -c              Check if input is sorted (exit 1 if not)
    -s              Stable sort (preserve order of equal elements)

EXAMPLES
    sort file.txt
        Sort alphabetically

    sort -r file.txt
        Sort in reverse order

    sort -n numbers.txt
        Sort numerically (1, 2, 10 not 1, 10, 2)

    sort -u file.txt
        Sort and remove duplicates

    sort -t: -k3 /etc/passwd
        Sort by field 3, colon-separated

    ls -l | sort -k5 -n
        Sort ls output by size (field 5)

    ls -lh | sort -k5 -h
        Sort by human-readable size

    sort -f names.txt
        Case-insensitive sort

    sort -rn scores.txt
        Reverse numeric (highest first)

    sort -c sorted.txt
        Check if already sorted

    sort -o output.txt input.txt
        Write to file

SEE ALSO
    uniq, head, tail, cut
